text:
Myrtle Avenue, north side, east from Prince Street, showing sidewalk displays of store goods and the curb pushcart market under the "EL." View 2 shows the same area, at a later date. Fort Greene Houses, a low-rent housing project, will later rise here.

P. L. Sperr

View 1: June 29, 1934
View 2: October 12, 1940

Myrtle Avenue, north side, east from Prince Street, showing sidewalk displays of store goods and the curb pushcart market under the "EL." View 2 shows the same area, at a later date. Fort Greene Houses, a low-rent housing project, will later rise here.

View 1: June 29, 1934
View 2: October 12, 1940

Prince Street, west side, north from Myrtle Avenue, showing more of the west side of the street. The low building with the high water tank is the Dugal Campbell auto display salon, formerly the car barn of the Manhattan Bridge trolleys. The view is from underneath the Myrtle Avenue elevated structure.

October 12, 1940

P. L. Sperr
